{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17650698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17650698"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:14:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:14:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18415"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18415"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11133"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74521"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11133"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18415"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60013"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7624"},{"type":"tags","id":"10244"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25803"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25805"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74521"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following findings is most characteristic of mitochondrial myopathies on muscle biopsy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nuclear inclusions","Increased glycogen storage","Central core lesions","Presence of \u0027ragged red\u0027 fibers","Perivascular lymphocytic infiltration"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMitochondrial myopathies are a group of disorders caused by dysfunction of the mitochondria, often leading to muscle weakness and exercise intolerance. On muscle biopsy, the most characteristic finding is the presence of \u003Cstrong\u003E\u0027ragged red\u0027 fibers\u003C/strong\u003E. These fibers appear due to the accumulation of abnormal mitochondria beneath the sarcolemma, which can be visualised using special stains such as Gomori trichrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased glycogen storage\u003C/strong\u003E is typically seen in glycogen storage diseases, not mitochondrial myopathies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerivascular lymphocytic infiltration\u003C/strong\u003E is more indicative of inflammatory myopathies, such as dermatomyositis or polymyositis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECentral core lesions\u003C/strong\u003E are associated with central core disease, a congenital myopathy, rather than mitochondrial myopathies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENuclear inclusions\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of inclusion body myositis, not mitochondrial myopathies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mitochondrial myopathies are characterised by specific histological findings on muscle biopsy.","\u0027Ragged red\u0027 fibers are a hallmark of mitochondrial myopathies, indicating abnormal mitochondrial proliferation.","Subsarcolemmal accumulation of mitochondria can be visualised with special stains such as succinate dehydrogenase (SDH)."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Longo, U. G., \u0026 Denaro, V. (Eds.). (2023). Textbook of musculoskeletal disorders. Springer Nature","Hughes, S. H. (2022). The Musculoskeletal System: The Musculoskeletal System-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Frontera WR, Ochala J. Skeletal muscle: a brief review of structure and function. Calcif Tissue Int. 2015 Mar;96(3):183-95. doi: 10.1007/s00223-014-9915-y. Epub 2014 Oct 8. PMID: 25294644","Morrison BM. Neuromuscular Diseases. Semin Neurol. 2016 Oct;36(5):409-418. doi: 10.1055/s-0036-1586263. Epub 2016 Sep 23. PMID: 27704495"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60013"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18415"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60013","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60013"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T06:05:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T06:05:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11133"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74521"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}